Residents in some of Cape Town’s informal settlements say authorities are letting them down following non-stop downpours this week. They claim the City is doing nothing to help after their homes were flooded. But the municipality says it has offered alternative accommodation. eNCA's Nobesuthu Hejana has the story. Courtesy #DStv403 CAPE TOWN - Residents in some of Cape Town’s informal settlements say authorities are letting them down following non-stop downpours over the past two days. They claim the City of Cape Town hasn’t done much to ease their plight after their homes were flooded. READ: Intense cold front expected to hit SA this week But the city says it’s offered alternative accommodation. Disaster Risk management says residents have been offered shelter in the local community hall, but refused to leave their belongings behind.